Step 3: Training Plan

6. How frequently will you run training? What format will it take (e.g., in-person, online, a combination of both)?

Initial Policy Introduction - Company Meeting - (Virtually)
  - All employees will receive initial training at the company “SilverCorp All-Hands Meeting:” 
      - General expectations will be discussed for ongoing cybersecurity training and how each training will be tailored to the security of each department.
      - Topics will include high-level details of the cybersecurity landscape and how it applies to SilverCorp.
      - Other topics will include password security, MFA authentication, using a VPN, device updates and how to report a threat and who should be notified.

Monthly Trainings - (In-person/Virtually)
  - A monthly newsletter will be generated to keep the organization aware of relevant threats and ways to protect their devices and company data.
      - The monthly newsletter may mention competitors or others in the industry that have experienced attacks.
  - Launch monthly phishing campaigns to test and monitor the number of employees clicking on fake email attachments.
      - Findings are reported to the department leadership to make them aware of how their teams are performing.
  - Monthly training will focus on what cybersecurity is, why it is important, the role each department plays, attack methods and how to prevent an attack.
      - Topics included content filtering, phishing, honeypots and spoofing to alert WFH employees of potential threats.

Quarterly - (Virtually/Online)
  - Zoom Calls with each department to cover relevant cybersec topics such as password security, phishing campaigns and malware awareness.
  - Mandatory testing of security knowledge would be required as recurrent training.
  - Hosting a quarterly meeting to share knowledge, findings and recommendations with the leadership team.
